04191nmm a2200565Ia 9780520393721DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20242024cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203937217 a10.1525/97805203937212doi  a(DE-B1597)672657  a(OCoLC)1390880290  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aLC196.5.U6bM27 2024 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a370.11/50973223/eng/202307191 aMarquez, Bayley J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPlantation Pedagogy :bThe Violence of Schooling across Black and Indigenous Space /cBayley J. Marquez. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Crossroads ;v7200tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPART ONE The Foundations of Plantation Pedagogy -- tIntroduction: Teaching Slavery and Settlement -- t1. Plantation Pedagogy, Educative Space, and Currents of Colonialism -- tPART TWO Plantation Pedagogy in the Currents -- t2. Plantation Pedagogy on the Reservation -- t3. Pacific Currents: Island Plantations and Industrial Schooling -- t4. Atlantic Currents: Industrial Education and Anti-colonial Struggle in Africa -- tPART THREE Plantation Pedagogy as a Technology of Settlement -- t5. “Out from Cabin and Tepee”: Settlement, Slavery, and the Making of Domestic Space -- t6. Teachers of Teachers: The Expansion of Plantation Pedagogy through Teacher Training -- t7. “Better Land, Better Stock, Better People”: The School as Experiment Station and Laboratory -- tConclusion: Learning by (Not) Doing? -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThroughout the nineteenth and twentieth centuries, teachers, administrators, and policymakers fashioned a system of industrial education that attempted to transform Black and Indigenous peoples and land. This form of teaching—what Bayley J. Marquez names plantation pedagogy—was built on the claim that slavery and land dispossession are fundamentally educational. Plantation pedagogy and the formal institutions that encompassed it were thus integrally tied to enslavement, settlement, and their inherent violence toward land and people. Marquez investigates how proponents developed industrial education domestically and then spread the model abroad as part of US imperialism. A deeply thoughtful and arresting work, Plantation Pedagogy sits where Black and Native studies meet in order to understand our interconnected histories and theorize our collective futures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxEducationzUnited States. 0aCritical pedagogyzUnited States. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLand tenurexHistoryxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEducationzUnited States. 0aSlaveryxHistoryxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520393721?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520393721423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520393721/original  a978-3-11-079135-8  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles